Governing Principles
Before the phases:
Nothing in Option A changes until a domain is validated in UDM. The existing EAV pipeline, rules engine stored procedure, pivot MVs, and RDM DI reports all continue running unchanged throughout the migration. UDM runs alongside — not instead of — until each domain passes validation.
Every phase delivers standalone value. If the programme pauses after any phase, what was built is still useful. Nothing is half-built infrastructure with no return until the next phase completes.
Distribution is the cutover point — not the pipeline. The switchover for any domain happens once — when distribution queries udm_{domain}_arb instead of the existing pivot MV. Everything before that point is invisible to consumers.
Phase 0 — Schema Foundation
Risk: Zero. Reversible: Yes — drop the schema.
What you do:
Deploy Tier 1 DDL (v3) to DEV, then TEST, then PROD via the standard release pipeline. Empty tables. No engine. No data.
What changes: A new UDM schema exists with 27 empty tables.
What stays the same: Everything. No existing pipeline is touched.
Value delivered: The schema is the contract. Every subsequent phase has a governed target to write to. The PO and architecture team can start populating the catalog manually immediately — no engine needed for that.
Phase 1 — Catalog Population
Risk: Very low — inserts only, no existing tables modified.
What you do — four parallel workstreams:
1a. Source system catalog
Seed udm_source_system from DW.src_sys_dim. One INSERT per source system. Every subsequent registration has a governed vendor_id.
1b. Reference data seeding
Register DW.src_sys_dim, CST_DIM, DIM_NAICS, DIM_GEOGRAPHY, DIM_COUNTRY as REFERENCE_SOURCE. Run the engine in REFERENCE_SOURCE mode only — no fact processing. Populates udm_ref_company, udm_ref_sector, udm_ref_region, udm_ref_country, and creates udm_entity_registry rows as side effect. This is a read from RDM and write to UDM — zero impact on RDM.
