1d. Precedence rules extraction — highest-value quick win
Extract the hardcoded vendor priority logic from the Option A rules engine stored procedure. INSERT those rules into udm_precedence_rules. Refactor the stored procedure to read from the table instead. Zero pipeline change — the procedure still runs on the same schedule producing the same output. But the rules are now:
Visible to the PO without reading PL/SQL
Auditable with effective dates
Changeable via a change request INSERT/UPDATE — not a code deployment
What changes: UDM catalog tables are populated. The Option A stored procedure reads from udm_precedence_rules instead of having rules hardcoded.
What stays the same: All existing pipelines, schedules, and consumer queries.
Value delivered:
Single platform inventory for the first time
Governed source system catalog
Auditable, config-driven precedence rules
Reference and entity data ready for engine use
Phase 2 — Detection Layer
Risk: Very low — reads schema dictionary and EAV data, writes only to dsc_ tables.*
What you do:
Deploy Tier 2 DDL (dsc_* tables). Run the structural detection procedure against RDM and STAGE schemas. Run EAV value detection against the Federated EAV table. Surface findings to PO via the review queue.
What changes: Detection processes run on schedule. PO reviews queue. Approved findings generate catalog entries in udm_attribute_map.
What stays the same: All existing pipelines unchanged.
Value delivered:
First time the platform knows what it has versus what is catalogued
Column drops and new attribute arrivals are detected rather than discovered reactively
udm_attribute_map begins to be populated — the DI specification exists
Phase 3 — Manifest and Lineage Instrumentation
Risk: Very low — additive only.
What you do:
Instrument the existing ETL jobs to write a manifest entry on each file arrival and a lineage row on each load completion. No existing logic changes — just two additional INSERTs per load execution. This can be done as a wrapper around existing jobs or as a post-load trigger.
What changes: udm_delivery_manifest and udm_lineage start accumulating data.
What stays the same: All existing pipeline logic unchanged. Distribution unchanged.
Value delivered:
First time you have a governed audit trail of every load
Delivery completeness tracking — partial bundles are now visible
Lineage is populated before the engine runs — historical context for the first domain migration
Phase 4 — First Domain Parallel Run
Risk: Medium — new engine runs alongside existing, but distribution unchanged.
This is the first real engine work. Choose the domain with the most pain in Option A — typically the one with the most EAV attributes, the highest pivot cost, or the most frequent consumer complaints about stale data.
What you do:
Build the harmonisation engine (Module 6) for one domain only. Create udm_{domain}_stk and udm_{domain}_arb. Run the engine on the same schedule as the existing Option A pipeline — after each vendor load completes. Both pipelines produce output independently.
Run the validation suite — compare udm_{domain}_arb against the existing Option A pivot MV row by row. Document every discrepancy. Resolve each one. This is not a bug — it is the validation gate.
